INTRODUCTION¶

The Vehicle Silhouettes dataset contains the measurements of different vehicles such as model cars, vans, and buses. This dataset is taken from OpenML repository at https://www.openml.org/d/54(Vanschoren, 2021).

DATA SOURCE¶

The original source of dataset is collected from the Turing Institute, Glasgow, Scotland by Drs.Pete Mowforth and Barry Shepherd.

"This data was originally gathered at the TI in 1986-87 by JP Siebert. It was partially financed by Barr and Stroud Ltd. The original purpose was to find a method of distinguishing 3D objects within a 2D image by application of an ensemble of shape feature extractors to the 2D silhouettes of the objects. Measures of shape features extracted from example silhouettes of objects to be discriminated were used to generate a classification rule tree by means of computer induction" ("UCI Machine Learning Repository: Statlog (Vehicle Silhouettes) Data Set", 2021).

DATASET DETAILS¶

The Features in the dataset are the measurements of Silhouettes which are measured using Hierarchical Image Processing System (HIPS). This system extracts the independent features utilising both classical moments-based measures such as scaled variance, skewness and kurtosis about the major/minor axes and heuristic measures such as hollows, circularity, rectangularity, and compactness. These features are collected using four "Corgie" model vehicles such as Chevrolet van, Saab 9000, a double decker bus, and an Opel Manta 400 which are classes. This dataset contains 19 features in which one is target feature or class variable and remaining 18 are independent attributes. A total of 946 instances are recorded among these 100 instances are reserved for validation by source and rest 846 are available in the dataset.

DATASET FEATURES¶

Feature Name Data Type Units Description
Class Nominal Unknown Contains four types of vehicles such as OPEL, SAAB, BUS, VAN
COMPACTNESS Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula square of average perimeter divided by area i.e. (average perim) ^2/area
CIRCULARITY Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula square of average radius divided by area i.e. (average radius) ^2/area
DISTANCE CIRCULARITY Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, area/(av.distance from border)**2
RADIUS RATIO Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, (max.radius-min.radius)/av.radius
PR.AXIS ASPECT RATIO Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, (minor axis)/(major axis)
MAX.LENGTH ASPECT RATIO Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, (length perp. max length)/(max length)
SCATTER RATIO Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, (inertia about minor axis)/(inertia about major axis)
ELONGATEDNESS Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, area/(shrink width)**2
PR.AXIS RECTANGULARITY Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, area/(pr.axis length*pr.axis width)
MAX.LENGTH RECTANGULARITY Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, area/(max.length*length perp. to this)
SCALED VARIANCE MAJOR Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, (2nd order moment about minor axis)/area along major axis
SCALED VARIANCE MINOR Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, (2nd order moment about major axis)/area along minor axis
SCALED RADIUS OF GYRATION Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, (maximum variance + minimum variance)/area
SKEWNESS ABOUT MAJOR Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, (3rd order moment about major axis)/sigma_min^3 major axis
SKEWNESS ABOUT MINOR Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, (3rd order moment about minor axis)/sigma_maj^3 minor axis
KURTOSIS ABOUT MINOR Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, (4th order moment about major axis)/sigma_min^4 minor axis
KURTOSIS ABOUT MAJOR Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, (4th order moment about minor axis)/sigma_maj^4 major axis
HOLLOWS RATIO Numeric Unknown This is calculated using the formula, (area of hollows)/(area of bounding polygon)

NOTE: -

  1. Where sigma_maj^2 is the variance along the major axis and sigma_min^2 is the variance along the minor axis.
  2. area of hollows= area of bounding poly-area of object.
  3. The area of the bounding polygon is found as a side result of the computation to find the maximum length.

TARGET FEATURE¶

Target feature is class variable which is a categorical variable. Therefore, this comes under classification problem.

GOALS & OBJECTIVES¶

The aim of this project is to classify the given vehicle silhouettes into one of the four vehicle types.

Removing Outliers¶

In [10]:
for i in vehicle.columns[:-1]:
    q1 = vehicle[i].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = vehicle[i].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    
    low = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
    high = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
    
    vehicle.loc[(vehicle[i] < low) | (vehicle[i] > high), i] = vehicle[i].mean()
In [11]:
vehicle.boxplot(figsize=(15, 32), vert = False)
plt.title("Fig 2 : Data without outliers", size = 24)
plt.show()

Understanding Descriptive variables¶

In [17]:
vehicle.hist(figsize = (19, 14))

plt.suptitle("Fig 4 : Understanding descriptive data.", size = 24)
plt.show()

The data is not normalised and is to be scalled. This data normalisation and transformations are done in the later phases.

• Circularity: circularity ranges from 33 to 60 and the highest circularity lies between 40 – 45.

• Compactness: Compactness ranges from 70 to 120 and the maximum compactness achieved in 90.

• Distance_circularity: Distance circularity ranges from 40 to 110 and the highest Distance circularity is achieved at 70.

• Elongatedness: Elongatedness ranges from 25 to 60 and the maximum elongatedness is achieved at 45.

• Hollows_ratio: Hollows_ratio ranges form 180 to 210 and the maximum hollow ratio is achieved between 195 and 200.

• Kurtosis_about_major: Kurtosis major ranges from 0 to 40 and majority lies between 0 and 10.

• Kurtosis_about_minor: Kurtosis minor ranges from 175 to 205 and the maximum is achieved at 190.

• Max.length_Aspect_ratio: Maximum length of aspect ration lies from 0 to 12 and the maximum is reached at 7.

• Max.length_Rectangularity: Maximum length of rectangularity ranges from 120 to 180 but highest rectangularity is achieved at 140.

• PR.Axis_Aspect_ratio: PR Axis Aspect ratio ranges from 50 to 75 whereas the maximum aspect ratio is achieved between 60-65.

• PR.Axis_Rectangularity: PR.Axis Rectangularity ranges from 17 to 28 and the maximum rectangularity lies between 18 to 20.

• Radius_ratio: radius ratio for any vehicle ranges from 100 to 250 and the maximum radius is achieved at 150.

• Scaled_Radius_of_gyration: Scaled Radius of gyration ranges from 110 to 270 and the maximum radius is achieved at 175.

• Scaled_Variance_Major: Scaled Variance Major ranges from 125 to 275 and the maximum variance major is achieved at 175.

• Scaled_Variance_Minor: : Scaled Variance Minor ranges from 200 to 1000 and the maximum variance for minor is achieved at 300.

• Scatter_Ratio: Scatter ratio ranges from 125 to 250 and the maximum scatter ratio is seen at 150.

• Skewness_About_major: Skewness about major ranges from 60 to 85 and the maximum skewness about major is achieved at 70- 75.

• Skewness_About_minor: Skewness about minor ranges from 0 - 15 and the maximum skewness about minor is achieved at 0.

Summary and Conclusions¶

• After loading the data, data types are observed and respective conversions are made.
• The data is now checked for missing values, obvious errors, or typos, white spaces and outliers and manipulated accordingly.
• The target variable is converted to upper case.
• After cleaning the data descriptive statistics on the numeric data are calculated.
• The data is now visualised and checked for normality. This is done in the phase 2 i.e., Data Modelling Data pre-processing.
• The data is skewed data. Hence, Normalisation and transformations are to be done.
• This scaling helps in the better prediction of the model i.e., more accurate predictions from the data can be obtained.
• Radios ratio and Scatter ratio are linearly co-related.
• SCALED_VARIANCE_MAJOR and SCALED_VARIANCE_MINOR are strongly related to each other. They show a high linear relation ship.
• Majority of the Sillouttes are of type BUS followed by SAAB, OPEL and VAN respectively.
• This classification will be predicted using 5 different Machine Learning models in Phase 2.
• But before Modelling Data is to be scalled.
• Then the data is split into Test, Train and Validation sets as required.
• The final predictions are then noted and analyzed.
